<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Buttle UK</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ritten evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Buttle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> UK</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary of written evidence</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Buttle UK is a grant-giving organisation supporting children and families. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evidence from our grant giving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">suggests that the changes made to support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for housing costs since 2011 have eroded the ability of the most vulnerable families to meet their children’s basic needs and increased their reliance on debt and charities to make ends meet. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a starting point we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believe that support to pay for housing costs should reflect in full the reality of the high housing costs faced by many vulnerable, low income families. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Looking ahead </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we have some specific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concerns about support for housing costs now and under Universal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Credit that, if addressed, could ameliorate hardship for some of the poorest and most vulnerable children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ideally w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e would like to see the social size criteria re-considered as a whole but as a very minimum we would like to see a more rea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">listic and generous approach to determining when a bedroom is “occupied”.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The exemption from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Shared Accommodation Rule</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for 25 to 35 year olds who have previously been homeless should be extended to all claimants under 35</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who have been homeless</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Univer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sal Credit should operate under a default position of avoiding suspensions where possible. If they are used, suspensions should be for short periods only and partial suspensions should be used wherever possible instead of full suspensions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In order to supp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ort families navigating the reforms, we would also like to see guidance issued to local authorities encouraging them to use their local welfare assistance schemes to offer as much support as possible to vulnerable families moving home. </span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Buttle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> UK is the largest grant-giving organisation in the UK to directly support individual children and their families. In 2012/13 we made 11,654 grants with a total value of £2.67 million. This is up by 26% in number and 25% in value over 2011/12. The grants w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere given for a range of essential items, but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with the majority, (83%), were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for cookers, fridges, washing machines and children’s beds and bedding. Through our grant programmes we hear about children and young people in circumstances of particular disadva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntage. All our awards are made to families and young people suffering from acute financial distress and material deprivation whilst reliant on means tested benefits. This makes us well placed to comment on the role of the social security system in meeting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the needs of claimants in vulnerable groups. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The benefit cap, the under-occupancy charge, the limiting of LHA to the 30</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> percentile of rents and the localisation and reduction of council tax </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">support have significantly eroded support for housing costs forcing families to dip in to their primary income benefits to meet their liabilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is now routine that families are ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pected to meet at least part of their housing costs from their primary income benefits and the amount varies substantially according to circumstance and location.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a result, we are seeing ever greater numbers of vulnerable children and young people whose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> basic needs for clothing, food, hygiene, and m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aterial goods are going unmet because their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">families</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’ already meagre incomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are diverte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d to paying for housing costs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Prior to April 2011 applications to our “Emergency Essentials” grant programme were increa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sing at an average of 1.6% per quarter. Following the first round of welfare reform in April 2011, including significant reductions to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Local Housing Allowance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LHA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the rate of increase has accelerated. We are now seeing an average increase in application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s of 3.8% per quarter from families requiring basics like beds and bedding, children’s clothing, cookers and washing machines. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Social sector size criteria</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocial sector size criteria in particular are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> causing hardship to many families. The regulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have very strict rules to determine when a bedroom is or is not occupied. This leads to an under occupation charge being applied to families who are clearly in need of the “unoccupied” bedroom and could not reasonably be expected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to move or take up employ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (as was the original policy intention)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The examples below demonstrate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">three </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very different circumstances in which families are in hardship as a result of this policy with very few options available to them to resolve their financial difficulties. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have recently seen a number of applications from expectant parents who have found </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">themselves subject to the charge when they have taken on a new tenancy in preparation for a new baby. This can leave parents struggling and building up debt at a time when t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hey are vulnerable and in need of support to build a secure home for their family. This is particularly damaging for young expectant parents, who are already receiving very minimal benefits at the young person’s rate. For example, a pregnant 19-year old re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ceiving £56.80 Income Support a week secures a 2-bedroom housing association flat to house herself and her unborn child. If the rent is £80 a week, she will be expected to pay £11.20 a week towards her rent up until the birth of her baby, leaving her just </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£45.60 a week to live on and prepare her home for her new child. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The following offers another example of how the social sector size criteria are damaging families in very different circumstances. An application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was made </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to Buttle UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on behalf of a family </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in desperate need of cl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">othing for the children. The mother</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the family is a lone parent of two children under three and a full time carer to her father who lives nearby. The family live in a three bedroom council house. Although the third bedroom is freq</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uently occupied by the grandfather when his health is at its worst, the family is now subject to an under occupation charge as well as increased council tax contributions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Before these costs were introduced in April the family would have been just above th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e poverty line (as measured by 60% median income after housing costs). These additional costs have pushed them below the poverty line, leaving them with increasing debts and struggling with their most basic needs such as children’s clothing. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A further pol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">icy intention of the social sector size criteria was that it would encourage both social landlords and tenants to ensure a better match between housing need and accommodation provided at the start of a tenancy. Recent evidence from our grant giving suggest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s that this is not always possible, and is causing particular difficulties for young single people moving in to social housing on their own. We are currently receiving a steady stream of applications on behalf of young people who have lead unsettled lives,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> often including periods of homelessness, and have be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en allocated social housing in two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> bedroom flats. These young people often feel little option but to accept the homes they have been allocated despite the financial hardship it will cause them as a resul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t of the under occupancy charge. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ideally w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e would like to see the social sector size criteria re-considered as a whole but as a very minimum we would like to see a more realistic and generous approach to determining when a bedroom is “occupied”.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Shared ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">commodation rule</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Housing Benefit r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">egulations and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Universal Credit r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">egulations provide an exception to the Shared Accommodation Rule for those claimants who are aged 25 to 35, have lived in a hostel for homeless people for a minimum of 3 months and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">accepted re-settlement support (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HB Amendment Regs 2012 (2) and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UC Regs Sch 4, Para 29 (4)). This is a welcome exemption as people who have experienced homelessness often face particular difficulties that would make living in shared accommodation impractica</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l or inappropriate. However we are very concerned that this same exemption does not apply to young</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> under 25 who have faced similar experiences. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the last year Buttle UK has supported </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over 1000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> young</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, single</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people ag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed 16 to 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o had</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">been made h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">omeless</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (and were also not care leavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Many of these young people also have health problems, or emotional or behavioural difficulties. It is increasingly difficult for this cohort of young people to access social housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(particularly one bedroom flats</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as described above) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and many have no option but to rent in the private sector on leaving supported housing. However for man</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y, shared accommodation is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> unworkable and could contribute to tenancy failure and further periods of homelessness. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> see this exemption extended to all renters under 35 who have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">previously been homeless. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Benefit suspensions</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current benefit system leaves claimants open to hardship when reporting changes of circumstances as payments are often suspende</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d pending a revi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sed decision. This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is a very common feature of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">grant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">appli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cations we receive, particularly from families</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that have recently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">moved home, had a partner move in or out or had a baby. Although there is guid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ance for Decision Makers that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should prevent this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">occurring, claims are frequently suspended for a long time and unnecessarily </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e.g. when the change of circumstances is likely to increase rather than decrease their entitlement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Under the current system, there is a safety net in that usually only one bene</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fit at a time will be suspended. It is very common for us to receive applications from families stating they are, for exa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mple, living on Child Tax C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">redits while their Housing Benefit is reassessed or vice versa. We are concerned that under the move to Univ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ersal Credit suspensions to benefit payments will cause very severe hardship and increases in rent arrears if payments are suspended in full and families are unable to pay their rent or pay for their daily living costs. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to ensure that Universal Credit operates under a default position of avoiding suspensions where possible. If they are used, suspensions should be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for short periods only and partial suspensions should be used wherever possible instead of full suspensions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Moreover, when suspensions are lifted, any money owed to the claimant should be paid i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mmediately rather than waiting for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their next payment date. This is particularly important in light of the switch to monthly payments. To ensure this happens Decision Mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ers will require stronger guidance than is currently available to them a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">computer system that supports flexibility in the suspension</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and reinstatement of payments. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local welfare assistance</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The new system of support for housing costs is designed to enc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ourage greater housing mobility by encouraging f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">amilies to move home </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in circumstances </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where the Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> considers their property to be too expensive or under-occupied. Moving home is expensive, often requiring families to pay deposits and agency fees as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> well as paying to transport belongings and purchase new household goods (for example when moving from a furnished to an unfurnished rental property). At the same time, the discretionary social fund, which has previously supported some of the most vulnerab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le families with these costs, has been devolved to local authorities with substantially reduced funding: a drop from £293m in 2010/11 to £178m in 2013/14. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In a recent survey of support workers who refer their clients to us 59% described the new local schem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es as less generous than the social fund and 68% said they were now more likely to apply to charities on their clients’ behalf. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">suggests to us that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduction in funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that has accompanied the localisation of welfare assistance</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has left many fami</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lies subject to increased debt and reliance on charities when trying to reduce their housing costs by moving home. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like to encourage the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to issue to guidance to local authorities encouraging them to use their local welfare assistance s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chemes to offer as much support as possible to vulnerable families moving home.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>